{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536545","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536545"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15801"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15801","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15801"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.62,0.05,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8492"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62635"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8492","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8492"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15801"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48083"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1374"},{"type":"tags","id":"4436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4438"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20405"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45340"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62635","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62635"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Birth Suite in active labour with her third child at 39 weeks gestation. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her previous deliveries were uncomplicated vaginal births. On examination, she appears distressed with strong contractions every two minutes. Her pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Vaginal examination reveals she is 8 cm dilated with a well-applied fetal head. She requests pain relief.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following analgesic options should be most cautiously considered?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nitrous oxide","Morphine","Water immersion","TENS machine","Massage"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario presents a multigravida woman in advanced labour who is likely to progress rapidly to delivery. The choice of analgesia must consider the high likelihood of imminent delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMorphine\u003C/strong\u003E should be most cautiously considered in this situation. It crosses the placenta and can cause significant neonatal respiratory depression if administered within 4 hours of delivery. Given this patient\u0027s parity and cervical dilatation of 8 cm, delivery is likely to occur within this timeframe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitrous oxide\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate choice as it has a very short half-life, can be discontinued immediately if needed, and does not cause neonatal respiratory depression. It provides rapid onset of pain relief and can be effectively used until delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWater immersion\u003C/strong\u003E is a safe non-pharmacological option that can provide significant pain relief without risk to the neonate. However, the woman would need to exit the bath for delivery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETENS machine\u003C/strong\u003E (Transcutaneous Electrical Nerve Stimulation) is a safe option that can be used until delivery, though it may provide limited benefit this late in labour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMassage\u003C/strong\u003E is a safe non-pharmacological option that can be continued throughout labour and delivery without any risk to mother or baby.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key consideration in advanced labour is to avoid long-acting opioids that could compromise neonatal respiratory function. Multiparous women typically progress more rapidly through labour than primiparous women, particularly in the late first stage and second stage of labour.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Morphine administered within 4 hours of delivery increases the risk of neonatal respiratory depression.","Rapid progression to delivery is common in multigravida women who are close to full dilatation.","Short-acting analgesics like nitrous oxide are preferred when delivery is imminent."],"references":["Queensland Health. Intrapartum Pain Management Clinical Guideline [Internet]. Brisbane: Queensland Health; 2021 [cited 2024 Nov 18]. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0014/1211126/g-intrapartum-pain.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48083"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15801"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48083","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48083"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-18T08:21:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-18T08:22:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8492"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62635"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":n